  "minneapolis-mn": {
    sec_material: `Minneapolis siding is dominated by wood lap siding and vinyl on 1920s-1950s bungalows and four-squares, with Hardie fiber cement on mid-range and higher-end renovations in Uptown, Linden Hills, and Lowry Hill. Brick appears on commercial-style residential and landmarked homes. The dominant Minneapolis siding specification is thicker vinyl (.046" or heavier) or fiber cement to handle the sustained -20F winter temperatures. Thin-gauge vinyl fails on impact at severe cold.`,
    sec_climate: `Minneapolis siding faces the most severe freeze-thaw environment in any major US metro: sustained -20F temperatures, 60+ inches of annual snowfall, and 100+ freeze-thaw cycles per year. Ice-dam water intrusion drives hidden moisture damage behind siding. Dimensional stability of the siding material matters more here than in any other metro: materials expand and contract dramatically across the seasonal temperature range, which stresses seams and fasteners.`,
    sec_code: `Minnesota Department of Labor and Industry requires a Residential Building Contractor license for jobs over $15,000. Minneapolis Heritage Preservation Commission covers districts including Milwaukee Avenue, Nicollet Island, Healy Block, and Fourth Avenue Historic District. Minneapolis also enforces Minnesota Energy Code mandating air leakage verification on whole-home weatherization.`,
    sec_insurance: `Minneapolis homeowners insurance covers wind, hail, and ice-dam water intrusion as sudden events. Most Minnesota carriers require demonstration of attic insulation (R-49 minimum) and ventilation adequacy before covering repeated ice-dam claims. Xcel Energy Minnesota and CenterPoint Energy offer envelope credits on qualifying whole-home retrofits.`,
    sec_contractor: `Minneapolis contractor verification: Minnesota LARA Residential Building Contractor license at minneapolismn.gov, plus Minneapolis city contractor registration. Minnesota also requires Residential Remodeler licensing for smaller jobs. Home Energy Squad conservation-improvement-funded jobs require verified licensing.`,
    sec_flag: `Minneapolis-specific siding fraud patterns concentrate on vinyl-gauge substitution and thermal-expansion-related damage concealment. The Minneapolis pattern: a contractor installs thin-gauge (.040") vinyl instead of bid-specified .046" or heavier, and the thin-gauge material cracks during the first -20F winter. Minneapolis-specific due diligence: physically verify the gauge printed on the product packaging before installation begins.`,
    dominantMaterial: "thicker vinyl and Hardie fiber cement on bungalow and four-square housing",
    climateBand: "very-cold continental with extreme freeze-thaw cycling",
    bestSeasons: "May through September above sealant-activation thresholds",
    worstSeasons: "November through April sustained sub-freezing conditions",
  },
  "charlotte-nc": {
    sec_material: `Mecklenburg County's explosive growth (4,800 residential building permits in 2024, the most in any NC county) has made Hardie fiber cement the default siding on new tract construction across the Ballantyne-Waxhaw-Fort Mill suburban ring, while brick veneer covers SouthPark, Providence Plantation, and the north-Charlotte Huntersville-Cornelius corridor. Original 1920s-1940s wood lap siding survives on Dilworth, Plaza Midwood, and NoDa craftsman bungalows, much of it carrying 3-7 layers of legacy paint including lead. Vinyl appears on value-tier replacements in East Charlotte and Cotswold but is prohibited by HOA covenants in SouthPark, Ballantyne, and most Lake Norman communities.`,
    sec_climate: `Charlotte siding contends with Piedmont red-clay shrink-swell cycles that stress framing connections, Charlotte Regional Tornado Alley exposure (the March-May severe-weather corridor running from Gaston County through southwest Mecklenburg), and oppressive 80-90% RH from June through September that breeds Cladosporium and Aureobasidium mold on north-facing elevations within 10-14 months. The 2022 Christmas arctic blast cracked vinyl and thin-gauge fiber cement across thousands of Piedmont homes when temps dropped from 60F to 9F in 18 hours. Formosan subterranean termites are an escalating threat, with Mecklenburg County Extension reporting colony expansion into Dilworth and Plaza Midwood neighborhoods since 2021.`,
    sec_code: `North Carolina Licensing Board for General Contractors (nclbgc.org) requires a state GC license for jobs exceeding $30,000. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Historic District Commission reviews exterior material changes on Dilworth (platted 1891, Charlotte's first streetcar suburb), Wesley Heights, Fourth Ward, Plaza Midwood, Wilmore, and Hermitage Court contributing structures. NC Residential Code amendments post-Hurricane Florence (2018) and the 2020 severe-weather outbreak tightened flashing and wind-uplift specifications on all exterior cladding replacements.`,
    sec_insurance: `Charlotte carriers tightened siding-condition underwriting sharply after the 2023 hail outbreak that generated 15,000+ Mecklenburg County claims. Class 4 impact-rated fiber cement now earns 10-20% premium reductions, and the Charlotte Regional Tornado Alley corridor justifies the Class 4 upgrade cost on virtually every Ballantyne and SouthPark property. Duke Energy Carolinas Smart $aver offers $0.50-$0.75 per square foot on qualifying insulated-siding envelope retrofits.`,
    sec_contractor: `Verify NC GC license at nclbgc.org (mandatory for jobs over $30,000) and Mecklenburg County contractor registration for permit-pulling on smaller scope. NC Consumer Protection complaints searchable at ncdoj.gov. SouthPark, Ballantyne, and Lake Norman HOA architectural review committees require written pre-approval of material and color before any order ships -- skipping this step is one of the most common Charlotte siding project failures, forcing expensive rework after HOA rejection at final walkthrough.`,
    sec_flag: `Charlotte-specific fraud concentrates on two patterns: first, tornado-corridor post-storm canvassing where out-of-area crews bid HOA-compliant Hardie fiber cement, collect deposits, and install non-compliant vinyl or thin-gauge (5/16 inch) fiber cement that fails the HOA final review; second, termite-damage concealment where new siding is installed over Formosan subterranean termite infestation without disclosure or remediation. Charlotte-specific due diligence: require written HOA approval before material orders, physically verify Hardie thickness (5/16 vs 7/16) on the delivery truck, and demand a current CL-100 termite letter before signing any Dilworth or Plaza Midwood siding contract.`,
    neighborhoodNote: `Dilworth and Plaza Midwood historic overlay districts enforce the Charlotte Historic District Commission design standards, which mandate that replacement siding match the original material profile within 1/4 inch tolerance. Ballantyne and Waverly master-planned communities have CC&R-mandated 10-year re-paint cycles enforced by the HOA, creating predictable contractor demand every March-April. The I-485 belt suburban ring from Huntersville to Indian Trail uses builder-grade vinyl that reaches end-of-life at 15-18 years, creating a rolling replacement wave across the southern suburbs.`,
    dominantMaterial: "Hardie fiber cement on suburban tract and brick veneer on SouthPark and Providence construction",
    climateBand: "humid-subtropical Piedmont with tornado corridor",
    bestSeasons: "October-November and March-April outside pollen peak and humidity surges",
    worstSeasons: "February-March pollen, July-August humidity, and spring storm cycles",
  },

